#1165
@@dThornwood Hall - The Grand Entrance@@N~
@@dThe entrance hall is tall enough that the upper reaches are lost in darkness, and wide
enough that four men could walk abreast. A grand staircase dominates the far end,
its banister carved from a single piece of black wood into a continuous procession of
thorned vines bearing blossoms that look too much like open mouths. The floor is
marble, cracked and stained dark in patterns that suggest old drainage channels. The
smell of the place is deep stone and something floral that should not be here in any
season. Portraits line the walls, each one damaged in the same way: the eyes removed.@@N
