#1172
@@dThornwood Hall - The Portrait Gallery@@N~
@@dThe gallery runs the length of the east wing's ground floor, lit by south-facing windows
so caked in grime the light arrives grey and diffuse. The portraits here are intact,
spanning what appears to be several generations of the same family, recognizable by
the distinctive pale eyes and the particular way each subject holds their left hand:
fingers spread, palm inward, as though pressing against glass. The final portrait at
the gallery's end shows the entire family, twenty or more figures, standing in this very
hall. The room's wallpaper has the pattern of thorned briars.@@N
