@@dThe Back Scullery@@N~
@@dThe scullery is cold and dim and smells of iron and fat. Racks of blackened pans
occupy the walls; a stone sink the size of a bathtub is stained deeply despite what
must have been years of scouring. The window above the sink looks into the kitchen
garden and is too small to pass through without difficulty. A half-consumed block of
tallow candle on the sill suggests someone stands here at night to watch the garden.
