#1195
@@dThornwood Hall - The Study@@N~
@@dThe study is the most lived-in room in the hall, which is to say it shows signs of
habitation within recent memory. Books pulled from shelves and left open on every
surface; papers covered in dense writing stacked in unstable columns; a fire laid
but unlit; a high-backed chair at the desk, its armrests worn smooth. The desk holds
an open journal whose final entries concern preparations for a ritual described in terms
that make clear the writer expected it to go wrong and proceeded regardless. The
window behind the desk looks directly into the heart of the thornwood.@@N
